Habitat, our tech product aimed at increasing awareness to induce behavioral change and
prevent inefficient energy usage, was divided into two core parts: data gathering and suggestion
providing. Data would be collected through a network of current sensors attached to the
fuseboxes in dorms and then be corroborated with a second network of sensors monitoring
outside temperature, room occupancy, and brightness. If the sensors detected unnecessary
energy usage, students would receive a notification alerting them with a suggestion for how to
do better. By utilizing behavioral change techniques such as monetary rewards, the Tamagotchi
effect, and community leaderboards, Habitat incentives students to follow our suggestions and
increase sustainability.
[INSERT INDIVIDUAL ROLE]
Our original proposal was based heavily on reducing the over 120 million kilowatt hours of
electricity used yearly through more intense preventative measures. Rather than provide
suggestions to try and change individual behaviour, we intended to implement tech that would
automatically correct inefficient usages. An early example was to require students to tap their
student ID any time they wanted access to power, which would then open a running tab they
would have to close when done to avoid penalties. In doing so, we had hoped we would be able
to reduce unnecessary energy usage, lowering both the environmental impact of NYU as well
as the university’s power bill.
However, after valuable feedback from both our mentor and user interviews, we realized this
was way too invasive and borderline something out of George Orwell’s 1984. Additionally, the
physical hardware needed to implement this idea onto every source of power at NYU was
unfeasible when compared to the potential savings. Deeming the project both too ambitious and
inconvenient to students, we reappropriated the idea to focus only on dorm rooms and utilize
suggestions instead.
Day of Hackathon:
Our main goal during the hackathon was to develop the MVP of the statistics display that would
be placed around traffic-heavy areas of campus, such as elevators and lobbies. The prototype
consisted of an RFID reader, a Raspberry Pi, and a miniature monitor. The prototype worked as
such: the ID would be tapped on the RFID reader attached to the monitor, the GUI would show
the current statistics and suggestions in the student’s specific dorm, and the GUI would
disappear after 10 seconds, allowing other students to view their data.
In the morning, Dylan and Andrew went to B&H Photo and video to pick up a small 4x6in
monitor and cable that would be used to display the GUI.
Drawing of display panel GUI
3D rendering of display panel GUI
Dylan and Anna made the prototype, outlined below was their process:
We took advantage of the side room in the venue that occupied a monitor we could use to read
and run code on the Raspberry Pi. The monitor served as a bigger screen compared to the
miniature one for our prototype to make it easier to run tests. We used a laptop to edit code via
Vim and to SSH into the Raspberry Pi. We also used the soldering iron onsite to solder the
header pins on the RFID reader.
Anna soldering
Anna and Dylan wiring the prototype
The external RFID reader in the picture below gave us an ID that had leading zeros, which was
not compatible with the code that we created to detect an ID being tapped on the RFID sensor.
External RFID reader
We implemented code to get the RFID ID number so that we could perform an action based on
a certain RFID card tapped, which did not return IDs with leading zeros so it workewd perfectly
with our code. Using the correct RFID ID numbers, we could detect which card was tapped on
the RFID sensor. Next, we achieved the functionality of opening up an image file when the RFID
reader detected a ID tapped, and it would disappear after 10 seconds. The last component of
our prototype was opening up different images corresponding to different IDs.
The first issue we encountered was connecting to WiFi/hotspot since both the laptop and the
RPI needed to be connected to the same network. At first, we connected both to the public WiFi
at the venue but we were unable to SSH into the RPI, possibly due to too many connections on
the same network. We switched to a hotspot provided by Dylan and we were able to SSH into
the RPI.
Anna also had unfamiliarity with some functionality, such as using RFID readers and using
various packages, so she had to do some extra debugging.
Another roadblock in the monitor-RPI-laptop dilemma was Dylan’s external keyboard. His
keyboard did not have any labels on the keycaps, so it was difficult to type looking back and
forth between the keyboard and the external monitor on the wall. Dylan was tasked for the rest
of the day to type on the keyboard when needed to avoid further frustration
.
The keyboard in question…
The finalized prototype had the RFID reader and RPI mounted to the back with an external
battery to power the RPI.
Final prototype
Presentation
Our presentation focused on the impact behind our product and the idea that we wanted to
change behavior and build habits. Describing the influence that our product could have on
NYU’s sustainability plan was essential to conveying the validity of the entire system.
We gave Professor Bhatia one of the sample student IDs to give an interactive element to our
presentation. Overall, the presentation went smoothly and our prototype worked as planned.
The slide for the mockup of the GUI with the ferret (slide 4) was the most memorable, as we
received loud reactions fron the audience. The presentation went go over time, but that could be
improved in the future with more practice and reducing our rambling.
Before our presentation, we were worried about how we would show the audience the demo, as
the miniature screen we bought would not be visible to the audience. An option was to bring the
judges into our room and show them the process on the monitor, but we decided to show the
judges the demo and display the slide of the mockup GUI to the audience.
Future Investment and Scalability Testing
If provided with a $5,000 investment opportunity, we would spend the money on beta testing our
device on actual floors of real NYU dorms. The plan would be to target a single building, ideally
one with minimal rooms. We would install the fuse-box current monitors in every room, and
place a few of the RFID-enabled screens around key public locations such as lobbies, lounges,
and by elevators. The quantity and placement of these screens would be minimal at first, in
order to reduce costs. Thankfully, this shouldn’t affect functionality since students would still be
able to view stats on their mobile devices.
This installation would essentially be a guinea pig test, measuring both student response and
energy usage. If the installation is well received by students and energy usage does in fact go
down within range of our predicted numbers, then there would be indiciation to scale the project.
While the predicted ROI is 7 months, the trial period could be less if it shows a trend of
continued progress. Since the device network is inherently centered around collecting data, the
metrics of success would be easily visible, assuming all goes well and students actually listen to
the suggestions.
